  "body": "- [ ] I've [opened a support ticket](https://trufflesuite.zendesk.com/hc/en-us/requests/new) before filing this issue.\r\n\r\n---------------------------\r\n\r\n## Issue\r\n\r\nAdd a command to `@truffle/core` and `@truffle/config` to support a backup/restore command/feature. I think this should only exist for the user-level config and not the project config but I figure we can use this as a jumping point for the discussion, or filling in my knowledge of the config package. \r\n\r\n## Steps to Reproduce\r\n\r\nN/A New feature request.\r\n\r\n## Expected Behavior\r\n\r\n1. Given a command like:\r\n\r\n``` bash\r\n$ truffle config backup [directory]\r\n```\r\n\r\n``` bash\r\n$ truffle config restore [filepath]\r\n```\r\n\r\n## Actual Results\r\n\r\n1. The `directory` param should default to the same directory as the existing config.\r\n2. Backup should create a new file that copies the previous user-level config with `.bkp` appended to the existing `filename.extension`\r\n3. The `filepath` param should default to the same directory and filename as the config with a `.bkp` extension. \r\n4. If a `directory` option is provided, the config package should verify the path exists before attempting to save a copy of the user-level config.\r\n5. `backup` should not overwrite an existing `.bkp` file in the `directory`.\r\n6. `restore` should validate the config file before attempting to overwrite the existing config.\r\n7. Neither command should be destructive, e.g. files will remain after running either command\r\n\r\n## Environment\r\n\r\n* Operating System: \r\n* Ethereum client:\r\n* Truffle version (`truffle version`):\r\n* node version (`node --version`):\r\n* npm version (`npm --version`): \r\n",
